Freeeeeedom!!!!
Today was the day y'all! These ladies got the boot from the winter coop and are in the summer coop on pasture! Man, this felt so good to get done today! 🙌💪
These girls were so ready to get out and we were so excited that we had this GORGEOUS day to get them out. 🙏☀️😎
The girls will be out all summer and we'll move them to fresh pasture every couple of days. They'll get the benefit of fresh grass and bugs galore and we get the benefit of chicken manure on our pasture. #winwin 👍
Don't worry, the coop is now covered, we left it uncovered to help coax the girls into the coop. The move went without a hitch which for anyone who farms knows what an event that is! 🤗

Maybe cheesy but totally awesome. \nMy love for the state of Michigan ultimately turned into a small business owner as my natural desire to explore this state turned into little hobbies over time. I have favorite spots from the Keewenaw Peninsula all the way down to the southeast corner of the state. However, my biggest love is Leelanau County. I started picking Petoksey and Leland Blue stones a while back and over time, I had gathered a huge collections of these historic stones, I started dabbling in making jewelry out of them. A "Pink" Full Moon of April rising above the clouds shining over Round Lake in Charlevoix. I pushed this image way ahead of queue because it was just so cool to see that moon. 
This is a 2-piece composite. One shot at 1/10th of a second to maintain detail in the moon and another shot at 4 seconds long to bring up the shadow details and smooth out the water's surface a bit.

-I have an amazing support group of girls that keep me motivated everyday.
-Lastly I know pushing play and showing my journey can help others believe in themselves and motivate them to continue their journey.
-I don’t cut out major food groups, so that means I never starve. I actually eat so much more then I use to and that truly is key. Eating right for your body. I may have tricks of tricking my mind that something taste the same as a unhealthy choice, but it all starts with trying.

What is Cuticle Oil ? 
Although this oil is named cuticle oil, it is helpful for overall nail care. The main task of a cuticle oil is to moisturize the nail and keep it soft. Many times we find that our nails become hard, brittle and unmanageable. In that case, it is not easy to cut them, or apply nail polish. Brittle and weak nails may also pose problems like working and even lead to scratches on skin just simply by touching. Healthy Homemade Lip Balm for Chapped Lips

Homemade lip balm generally doesn't contain the man-made chemical moisturizers that commercial lip balms do, such as petroleum jelly. Because the skin on your lips tends to be sensitive, especially when it's chapped, many people can't tolerate the harsh chemicals and preservatives in mainstream commercial lip balms. Homemade lip balm contains only natural ingredients, and it's far more gentle on your lips and on the planet.

Benefits 
Homemade lip balm contains several basic ingredients. Honey is important because, according to "Better Basics for the Home," it's a natural humectant that draws moisture from the air to keep your lips plump and moisturized. Last week Potter Park Zoo said goodbye to Little Girl, our 20 year old female snow leopard. Little Girl was the oldest snow leopard in AZA accredited zoos at the time of her passing. Snow leopards have a median life expectancy of 15 years, and we were very fortunate to have Little Girl reach the milestone of 20 years. \u2063\n\u2063\nZookeeper Annie has worked with Little Girl for over 14 year. \u201cIt has been privilege to work with little girl over the last 14+ years. She has been a joy to work with. Because of her tremendously positive relationship with her zookeepers and vet staff, she contributed to the care of other snow leopards. Information we learned with regular voluntary ultrasounds during her pregnancy was published and added to the body of knowledge other zoos can pull from. But I\u2019ve realized that what I look like doesn\u2019t define myself and confidence and self love can make anyone beautiful. I\u2019m a thick girl with a very healthy life style. I take care of myself and I practice self love as often as I can. I\u2019ve recently have been trying to accept the fact I\u2019m bigger and people will either leave it or take it. Positioning myself to a world where my looks define what kind of love I deserve has always been very self destructive for myself. We toss them with simple ingredients: a minimal amount of sugar, plus cinnamon, nutmeg, lemon juice, a little unbleached flour. We fill our handmade, hand-rolled pastry with a heaping pound of apples, and then top with pastry or crumble, your choice. At some point after pies are in the oven, I have to say out loud, \u201cIt smells so good in here!\u201d The response from Debbie and Alan is almost always \u201cGood! Happy Hump Day from Bhima! 💚

Bhima has asked that we share a little about him and his background, in answer to his constant flow of fan mail. 🐮

Bhima, is a Gyr ox, a breed originating from India.  Gyr ox are typically a very large breed, and Bhima weighs in at an astonishing 2,000 pounds! Interestingly enough, the hump on his back stores fat, not water, to be used as nourishment if food is scarce (luckily never a problem for him here at SASHA!). Before joining us at SASHA FARM Animal Sanctuary, Bhima and his brother, Dharma, were being raised on a Michigan farm to be used for field work, particularly pulling a plow.  The owner of the farm sold the property to a man who did not want cows, and Bhima and Dharma's future was in jeopardy. Yesterday it rained all day here in Washington DC. Most people would be upset about that during their travels, but for me I love it. I embrace it.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It gave me a chance to explore so many places while others were tucking away. It also reminded me of one of my favorite elopements I captured; this beautiful one on the beach.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
The couple was surrounded by their children and friend, who officiated the wedding. It was simple, sweet, and so touching. And right as they were married the rain came down, but they embraced it. I can still hear their laughter and it makes me smile.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
So I say hooray for rain! Are you a YAY or NAY for rain?"

• #WhyIAdviseWednesday: Luke, West Side Academy and Frederick Douglass Academy •

A college-going culture doesn't stop at a high school's doors. It's a community affair, and that's why Luke advises.

On Luke's first day as an adviser, the high school faculty invited the whole community to welcome students into the school. As students walked through the front door, they were met with music and cheers from the entire school faculty and available neighbors. The community lined up to greet them, one student at a time. It was beautiful for Luke to see, and to then become a part of.

Luke advises to be a positive influence on his students, better enabling them to explore higher education. But on a broader scale, he advises to inspire a movement and change a community's expectation of higher education pathways–so that his work will carry on long after this role ends.

Anaiya and Akayla have battled so much adversity during their journey thus far, while withstanding trials and tribulations that would overtake most people. Through staying focused on their aspirations, they have persevered and consistently been the role model for their two younger brothers. With their mother working extremely hard to provide for them all, I know this achievement means more than words could explain. The species is endemic to the western Atlantic Ocean. They are found off the coast of the southeastern United States as far north as Massachusetts, the Gulf of Mexico,& in the #Caribbean. They are also found in Bermuda and the eastern coast of Brazil.
The #fish inhabits marine & brackish waters. They are common in shallow waters along coastlines with depths of 3–35 meters. Juveniles commonly inhabit estuaries until maturity & adults prefer mangroves, beaches, and harbors.

Great cocktails and great steaks! I have been to this establishment many times, and for some reason I feel as though it\u2019s not as packed as it should be despite being located right on Route 23. It\u2019s a spacious restaurant so it looks a little dead when there\u2019s only a few tables or seats filled. Their cocktails tasted amazing, especially their frozen cocktails - perfect for a hot, sunny day. We ordered the steak and chicken and it was very tasty, especially the side of asparagus sauteed with garlic. Since finishing the original piece back in 2017, I’ve been eager to expand the piece into the wind band setting and take advantage of the different color possibilities in the accompaniment. Though the focus of the piece is primarily on the bass trombone, there are several technical passages, contrasting styles, and meter changes that will keep the wind ensemble players excited and engaged throughout the piece.

🍯 I LOVE sweet!!! So let’s talk honey. One of the first sources of sweetener I go to, along with pure maple syrup.
.
Not all honey is equal! I always go for RAW honey. It is more cloudy than the clear honey you see on the grocery store shelves. I also try to buy local if possible.
.
My nutrition plan allows for a couple of teaspoons a day. And YES I measure it out! Although it is HEALTHY it can still have the same damaging effect on blood sugar as white processed sugar, if you are using too much.
.
When we see a healthy alternative, often times we think “I can eat as much as I want” NO!!!! You cannot! I’m even reminded of a scripture verse that says “if you find honey, eat just enough, to much of it and you will vomit” 🤢
.

.
When I was a young lady I always had all my personal necessities inside my purse at all times. Now that I'm a mother, I just can't fit all that because there's plenty of stuff I must bring for my kid🙃. But there are things I absolutely must make room for—always.
.
Phone + cable + charger: Absolutely! And this not just for social media 😅. I must always have a means to reach and be reached by people. As such, I can't afford for it to be out of juice. Always carry a spare cable and charger.
.
Hand sanitizer: Kids ask for snacks all the time, and you don't always have someplace to have them wash their hands (or yours if you're handling it for them).
.

~

~

A kit of parts for temporary architecture from faculty member Laida Aguirre (@stock_a_studio) with @_delaneymccraney // These assembly systems aid in the composition of architectural elements and help maintain their physical integrity. Gary Mozer has arranged in excess of $30 billion of debt and equity financing for a broad array of real estate transactions. Appointed CEO in 1999, Gary has consistently ranked as GSP’s largest individual producer, placing up to $2 billion annually. He most frequently works in retail, multi-family, office, and industrial products, but is also an accomplished financier of hotels, assisted living and skilled nursing facilities, marinas, RV parks, and self-storage sites. His team at GSP is recognized for expertise in structuring complex transactions, mezzanine and equity.

Gary holds two graduate degrees from @UWMADISON a Master of Real Estate and a Master of Finance. His undergraduate education took place at @uofmichigan, where he earned a Bachelor’s of Science in Computer Science and Mathematics. Gary has remained involved with both Alumni associations.

A companhia Kellogg, conhecida principalmente pelos seus cereais matinais, anunciou esta semana que não vai mais financiar a realização de testes em animais, nem por meio de terceirização. O compromisso foi assumido com a organização Pessoas Pelo Tratamento Ético dos Animais (PETA), que celebrou a conquista em seu site.

Segundo a PETA, a Kellogg começou a financiar testes em animais há 65 anos, e desde então passou a utilizar principalmente camundongos. A primeira tentativa de um acordo para o fim da realização de teses em animais foi em 2007, quando a corporação disse que estava diminuindo o escopo de seus testes em animais.

A Kellogg foi fundada pelos irmãos Will Keith Kellogg e John Harvey Kellogg, que a princípio desenvolveram um cereal matinal de milho para atender as necessidades dos paciente

Here she is, my daughter\u2019s credenza for her room makeover.\nI\u2019ll be honest, when the piece was brought home, I wasn\u2019t sure it was going to be salvageable.  It was found on the side of the road in a snow bank, had been there all winter and was really bloated.  After she sat in my warm studio for a several days, she began to dry out and shape up!  Be sure to swipe to see more and the before pics.  She started coming alive once I sanded off the peeling varnish and water marks.  Not sure what type of wood (dust from sanding was a red clay color) but the grain is amazing!  I used @anniesloanhome Aubusson to highlight this girls beautiful shape and Clear Wax to seal everything.  I am super pleased with the results and my daughter loves it!  Happy Saturday my friends!\ud83d\udc30\ud83d\udc23\ud83d\

Shawshank Redemption:
This is a tale of a group of prisoners and their experience of coping with the fact that they depend on the very walls that block them from the outside world.

What I Liked: I love that the story is told from the perspective of Morgan Freeman. The acting was great and the skillful storytelling kept me invested. Brooks was my favorite part of the movie. The scene where he is freed is powerful and shows how difficult it is for an institutionalized man to re-adapt to the free world.

What I Disliked: I was bummed that there wasn’t a scene where the group of prisoners finds out how Tommy actually died.

I’ve heard a lot about this movie and am so thrilled that I finally saw it. The Shawshank Redemption lives up to the hype and is worthy of a 9/10 on the Average Viewer Scale!

|Busy Beaver| My family has been traveling to Northern Michigan my entire life. Last October, my dad and I were walking our property there and found that beavers had turned one of the small streams into a sizable pond. What impressed me the most was probably the scale of the project. They had downed 30+ trees with diameters ranging between a dinner plate and a beachball, which would have been used to make their dam. The pond itself submerged close to an acre (roughly the size of a soccer field) and had a beaver lodge sitting in the center where the water was deepest. From doing a bit of reading I learned that the lodge can have multiple chambers, each with its own private entrance from the outside. This one was about the size of a small car.
